00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:48.220
real-time travel updates,
and the ability to get a

00:01:48.220 --> 00:01:48.790
ticket on the phone.

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:49.440
RETO MEIER: So this is NSB.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:52.260
So this is the new front page.

00:01:52.260 --> 00:01:55.200
And as you can see, it shares a
little of the same thematic

00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:56.510
elements as the previous
version.

00:01:56.510 --> 00:01:59.300
But we've kind of lost that
dashboard pattern with the

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:01.930
big, giant, oversized buttons
which was one of the bits of

00:02:01.930 --> 00:02:03.300
feedback that had beforehand.

00:02:03.300 --> 00:02:05.870
So already, this is looking
a lot nicer.

00:02:05.870 --> 00:02:07.985
IAN NI-LEWIS: The design
here is really good.

00:02:07.985 --> 00:02:09.430
It's really clean.

00:02:09.430 --> 00:02:13.850
There's a lot of things
to like about it.

00:02:13.850 --> 00:02:18.200
The main thing that bothered me
when we first loaded it up

00:02:18.200 --> 00:02:19.990
is that so many things
are blank.

00:02:19.990 --> 00:02:22.400
So for instance, if you press
the button labeled Train

00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:28.060
journey, now you've used it a
little bit in the sense that

00:02:28.060 --> 00:02:29.200
you have a couple
of favorites.

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:33.492
I see they begin with A, just
like my favorites do.

00:02:33.492 --> 00:02:41.440
But before you have anything
in the favorites or the

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.380
journey, or before you've
performed any search, that

00:02:44.380 --> 00:02:46.630
area below the search
bar is simply blank.

00:02:46.630 --> 00:02:50.170
However, if you click in the
search bar, which you might

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:51.430
want to do right now, I
don't know actually

00:02:51.430 --> 00:02:52.170
what's going to happen.

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:56.620
So that brings up a list
of matching stations.

00:02:56.620 --> 00:02:59.690
And if you don't have anything
in the search

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:00.865
bar, they're all there.

00:03:00.865 --> 00:03:05.020
So my first piece of advice is
that should always appear.

00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:05.920
It's just logical.

00:03:05.920 --> 00:03:08.270
There's no reason that it should
suddenly appear when

00:03:08.270 --> 00:03:11.752
you click on the search bar
versus not being there to

00:03:11.752 --> 00:03:13.002
begin with.

00:03:15.050 --> 00:03:18.270
The favorites are more
or less the same way.

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:21.190
When you don't have any
favorites, it's literally just

00:03:21.190 --> 00:03:22.440
a blank screen.

00:03:24.620 --> 00:03:27.660
And the user has no way to
interact with it, which is

00:03:27.660 --> 00:03:29.320
disturbing.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:32.570
So my suggestion would be that
you actually have something at

00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:36.400
the top of the screen that,
for instance, an

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.390
Add Favorites item.

00:03:38.390 --> 00:03:41.490
I don't know how you go about
it, Roman, but I'm a big fan

00:03:41.490 --> 00:03:46.520
of lists whose last item
is Add Another Item.

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:48.320
ROMAN NURIK: That's kind of
following the principle of

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:52.910
direct manipulation, that the
actions that you can take on

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:55.310
the thing you're working on are
directly on top of what

00:03:55.310 --> 00:03:56.430
you're working on.

00:03:56.430 --> 00:04:00.170
So it's kind of like if you
remove an item from a list, so

00:04:00.170 --> 00:04:01.190
swipe it away.

00:04:01.190 --> 00:04:03.342
If you add an item to the list,
it's at the bottom of

00:04:03.342 --> 00:04:05.070
the list where that
item had appeared.

00:04:05.070 --> 00:04:08.150
You've added it to
that [INAUDIBLE].

00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:18.329
IAN NI-LEWIS: So if you plan
a journey, I think this is

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:19.589
really where it shines.

00:04:19.589 --> 00:04:24.093
You set a--

00:04:24.093 --> 00:04:27.280
RETO MEIER: I'm getting a
server error, which is

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:29.720
unfortunate.

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:30.700
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:33.660
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, you
can't see it on there.

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:37.920
So now you search for
a couple stations.

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:39.570
You plan a journey from them.

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:43.230
And with one exception, I think
it's a wonderful UI.

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:45.930
Unfortunately, with Reto's
server error, the one

00:04:45.930 --> 00:04:49.950
exception keeps popping up over
and over, which is the

00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:52.810
"Your ticket is valid
from" spinner.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.550
Props to making a spinner
that's flat.

00:04:55.550 --> 00:04:58.700
One thing we've noticed, though,
is that even though

00:04:58.700 --> 00:05:03.540
the spinner, back in 2006,
was just really trendy,

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:05.920
it hasn't aged well.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:09.490
It's not actually as convenient
a UI as you think

00:05:09.490 --> 00:05:10.060
it might be.

00:05:10.060 --> 00:05:13.590
And you've noticed that we've
moved off the spinner in some

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:17.130
of our apps towards more direct
things like numeric

00:05:17.130 --> 00:05:21.260
keypads that seem to
work a lot better.

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:24.960
ROMAN NURIK: And sometimes for
calendars, especially,

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:26.410
[INAUDIBLE] free, right?

00:05:26.410 --> 00:05:30.710
So you can actually use 30-day
month calendars that you flip

00:05:30.710 --> 00:05:32.670
up and down between the
different months.

00:05:32.670 --> 00:05:36.220
It's a little more square, so
it works better in different

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:37.300
aspect ratios.

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:40.055
It's scrollable, so it
definitely works for longer

00:05:40.055 --> 00:05:42.840
content with the
longer spaces.

00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:46.360
But it's just really easy to
wrap your head around.

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:49.460
So you can actually visually
see the days of the week.

00:05:49.460 --> 00:05:52.060
I think days of the week are
one of the most important

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:54.860
aspects of choosing a date,
especially when you're

00:05:54.860 --> 00:05:55.910
planning a trip.

00:05:55.910 --> 00:05:57.830
You're probably planning a
trip around a weekend, or

00:05:57.830 --> 00:06:00.260
around a specific date
like going out or

00:06:00.260 --> 00:06:01.950
[INAUDIBLE], whatever.

00:06:01.950 --> 00:06:06.740
And visually seeing the place
in the week that you're

00:06:06.740 --> 00:06:09.470
choosing something will give you
that extra bit of content.

00:06:09.470 --> 00:06:11.450
So I definitely recommend
something

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:12.860
like a month calendar.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:16.550
I think we've started using the
month, a 30-day view, in

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:17.915
some of our apps.

00:06:17.915 --> 00:06:18.830
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:06:18.830 --> 00:06:22.370
When I see something like this,
my first thought is, oh,

00:06:22.370 --> 00:06:27.322
I guess your project manager
has an iPhone.

00:06:27.322 --> 00:06:28.572
JON: I do.

00:06:33.370 --> 00:06:33.670
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:06:33.670 --> 00:06:35.970
It's unfortunate that we can't
quite get to the last bit

00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:39.330
where we actually
see the ticket.

00:06:39.330 --> 00:06:43.560
But I think one of the things
which I noticed in the

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.840
previous version, and I've seen
a little bit of it here

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:47.896
as well, is that every time
you do something which

00:06:47.896 --> 00:06:50.630
requires contact with the
server, we get a little

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:53.100
flash-up dialog telling us
that we're communicate

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:54.650
something with the server.

00:06:54.650 --> 00:06:56.930
That's something which I really
think takes away from

00:06:56.930 --> 00:06:58.920
the magic of how mobile
phones work.

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:00.860
We all know that it's connected
to the internet, and

00:07:00.860 --> 00:07:02.240
it needs to talk to
your server and

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:03.625
do all of that stuff.

00:07:03.625 --> 00:07:05.990
You kind of want your users to
think that it's just a magic

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:07.740
thing where your phone
just knows how

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:08.930
to pull train things.

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:11.550
And the fact that there's an
internet connection and mobile

00:07:11.550 --> 00:07:12.980
telephony all about
is just kind of

00:07:12.980 --> 00:07:14.400
completely hidden away.

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:16.390
So you want to try and make
sure that you're not

00:07:16.390 --> 00:07:18.520
displaying any of those sorts
of dialogs, particularly

00:07:18.520 --> 00:07:22.250
because usually, they just
come up really quickly.

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:26.830
You have sort of a flash
of talking to server.

00:07:26.830 --> 00:07:29.135
And if it all works,
it flashes away.

00:07:29.135 --> 00:07:31.770
And you just kind of think
as a user, what was that?

00:07:31.770 --> 00:07:32.285
Was that important?

00:07:32.285 --> 00:07:34.070
Should I have read that?

00:07:34.070 --> 00:07:36.410
So you really want to try and
just disguise all of that,

00:07:36.410 --> 00:07:38.220
unless something goes wrong.

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:40.800
And if it does go wrong, try and
be as descriptive as you

00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:44.380
can in a way that doesn't rely
on understanding how your app

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:46.390
is being implemented
to your user.

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:49.440
So something like, unable
to buy train tickets.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:51.420
No connection to
internet found.

00:07:51.420 --> 00:07:55.130
Something like that is more
useful than, server

00:07:55.130 --> 00:07:58.210
communication error, where the
user is like, I don't know

00:07:58.210 --> 00:07:59.375
what any of that means.

00:07:59.375 --> 00:08:01.250
Did I do something wrong?

00:08:01.250 --> 00:08:05.270
Rather than, OK, well, I can
try again later because my

00:08:05.270 --> 00:08:08.145
connectivity is down, which they
may be more easily able

00:08:08.145 --> 00:08:10.270
to understand.

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:13.910
IAN NI-LEWIS: So we just got the
schedule, which you may be

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:16.880
able to see here if I can
hold it still enough.

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:19.010
I realize that's coming
through very well.

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:20.900
You can see that's a really
clean design.

00:08:20.900 --> 00:08:23.000
It's got the nice red
band at the top.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:25.520
Everything else is monochrome,
but there's a fairly good

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:31.720
differentiation using fonts
and highlighting.

00:08:31.720 --> 00:08:36.450
I think based on the specific
application, and I'm not

00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:42.700
familiar with the trains of
Norway at all, but I can

00:08:42.700 --> 00:08:45.760
readily believe that they are
all color-coded in different

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:46.830
shades of gray.

00:08:46.830 --> 00:08:48.860
But if they're not, and if
there is any kind of

00:08:48.860 --> 00:08:54.800
color-coding, that might be a
really nice additional effect

00:08:54.800 --> 00:08:57.020
is to add some more information
that's going to

00:08:57.020 --> 00:09:00.400
help people find the platform
for the particular train that

00:09:00.400 --> 00:09:02.480
they're looking for.

00:09:02.480 --> 00:09:05.110
But this does a pretty
good job of not

00:09:05.110 --> 00:09:08.350
being too busy, I think.

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:09.040
I don't know.

00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:11.300
If I were to redesign this, I
might just use a thin font on

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:12.750
the city names.

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:15.530
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah, that's one
of the best ways to add a

00:09:15.530 --> 00:09:20.100
touch of elegance to your apps
as well as help even further

00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:23.310
the visual hierarchy that
you get from text.

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:26.630
Use different weights of Roboto,
different sizes--

00:09:26.630 --> 00:09:31.070
not too many different sizes, at
most maybe two or really at

00:09:31.070 --> 00:09:32.426
most three different sizes.

00:09:32.426 --> 00:09:34.873
But different font weights would
really help [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:34.873 --> 00:09:35.800
the hierarchy.

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:38.510
But yeah, like you said,
the hierarchy is

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:41.850
very evident as is.

00:09:41.850 --> 00:09:45.402
IAN NI-LEWIS: I think Roman
would probably say that

00:09:45.402 --> 00:09:48.624
putting the entire time in
the same weight is wrong.

00:09:48.624 --> 00:09:51.303
Of course, the hours should
be bold, and the minutes--

00:09:51.303 --> 00:09:53.030
just kidding.

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:54.150
Yeah, this looks really good.

00:09:54.150 --> 00:09:58.400
And especially, I don't know if
you can see it, but I love

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:01.040
the way that the platform
is in a little box.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:04.430
They make it really easy to see
it and also is a little

00:10:04.430 --> 00:10:06.390
kind of elegant.

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:08.360
So that's very nice.

00:10:08.360 --> 00:10:10.330
RETO MEIER: Yeah, I
have to say, the

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:11.536
biggest feedback I have--

00:10:11.536 --> 00:10:13.750
I have a page of notes which
I've tried to take

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:15.150
on each of the apps.

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:17.420
And they were all based
on version 4.

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:20.170
And version 5 fixes
all of them.

00:10:20.170 --> 00:10:23.870
So my feedback is nice
job on version 5.

00:10:23.870 --> 00:10:27.310
You've really updated the app,
brought it into the modern age

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:30.780
of Android where it's action
bar, Holo theme, a nice,

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:31.970
clean, flat line.

00:10:31.970 --> 00:10:33.790
There's a lack of clutter.

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:35.410
Simple, intuitive navigation.

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:38.870
So all of the little niggles
that I had around making it

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:41.010
sort of more of a modern,
up-to-date app, I think you've

00:10:41.010 --> 00:10:42.100
absolutely nailed.

00:10:42.100 --> 00:10:44.200
So nicely done.

00:10:44.200 --> 00:10:46.600
ROMAN NURIK: The one thing I
wanted to mention is about the

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:47.710
home screen.

00:10:47.710 --> 00:10:49.180
We spent a little bit
of time talking

00:10:49.180 --> 00:10:50.720
about onboarding flows.

00:10:50.720 --> 00:10:53.540
And I think that outside of the
Google playlist thing, the

00:10:53.540 --> 00:10:56.490
very first thing you see in the
app is probably your most

00:10:56.490 --> 00:10:57.510
important screen.

00:10:57.510 --> 00:10:59.140
It's almost a hero moment.

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:02.960
So I would spend even more time
on this landing screen to

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:03.980
tweak it a bit.

00:11:03.980 --> 00:11:06.410
Right now, it feels
very static.

00:11:06.410 --> 00:11:09.470
That's one of the problems, one
of the reasons we've moved

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:11.710
away from the dashboard pattern
and anything that

00:11:11.710 --> 00:11:13.110
basically just has
links on it.

00:11:13.110 --> 00:11:16.680
We've moved more towards a
content-driven home screen.

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:18.760
So one of the things that you
may want to consider doing is

00:11:18.760 --> 00:11:19.880
things like profile.

00:11:19.880 --> 00:11:23.800
You want to move it to the
action bar, since it is

00:11:23.800 --> 00:11:28.340
navigation, but it's often
treated as an action.

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:31.580
It's kind of like a common thing
is to put the profile in

00:11:31.580 --> 00:11:33.340
the overflow or something.

00:11:33.340 --> 00:11:35.640
And then things like "View
ticket," if you don't have a

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:38.570
ticket, is there any reason to
show that, I'm guessing?

00:11:38.570 --> 00:11:41.750
But you could also just
have it as a--

00:11:41.750 --> 00:11:44.070
I don't want to say card, but
have it as a scrollable item

00:11:44.070 --> 00:11:45.880
you can get to.

00:11:45.880 --> 00:11:48.555
IAN NI-LEWIS: Another thing to
think about is, this would be

00:11:48.555 --> 00:11:51.070
a perfect opportunity
to use some of

00:11:51.070 --> 00:11:53.910
the new action detection.

00:11:53.910 --> 00:11:58.930
Because if you know that the
person is in the middle of a

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:02.600
train journey, then probably the
first thing they want to

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:03.950
do is view a ticket.

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:05.996
That's probably why they pulled
