we call the Finn cat.

00:35:53.745 --> 00:35:55.210
We have a mascot.

00:35:55.210 --> 00:35:58.010
It's really weird, but we have
a mascot that is a cat, and

00:35:58.010 --> 00:36:00.530
he's really sarcastic, and he
makes all these sarcastic

00:36:00.530 --> 00:36:02.540
comments about different
things.

00:36:02.540 --> 00:36:08.270
So that's the cat that's sort
of posting all these little

00:36:08.270 --> 00:36:09.480
updates onto the stream.

00:36:09.480 --> 00:36:13.950
So the idea is to have a mix of
updates from that cat but

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:17.210
also like new hits on the
searches that you're making.

00:36:17.210 --> 00:36:19.160
RETO MEIER: I would love
to get updates

00:36:19.160 --> 00:36:19.940
from a sarcastic cat.

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:23.126
That sounds like the coolest
feature so far.

00:36:23.126 --> 00:36:26.200
ROMAN NURIK: That's such a
great way to form a true

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:30.420
emotional bond with your user is
to give them a personality

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:32.140
that they're working with,
almost like when they open the

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:34.122
app, they're kind of
talking to the cat.

00:36:34.122 --> 00:36:35.890
RETO MEIER: Yeah, I particularly
like the idea

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:38.230
that it's a sarcastic
cat, too.

00:36:38.230 --> 00:36:40.440
It's not like a helpful,
friendly cat.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:41.190
ALEX: Makes all the
difference.

00:36:41.190 --> 00:36:44.675
RETO MEIER: It's totally in your
face, making fun of you.

00:36:44.675 --> 00:36:46.120
And I think that's excellent.

00:36:46.120 --> 00:36:47.790
IAN NI-LEWIS: I hope not.

00:36:47.790 --> 00:36:50.930
So I think the one thing that
I'm seeing on the home screen

00:36:50.930 --> 00:36:54.830
is I'm very comfortable with the
design, but it does seem

00:36:54.830 --> 00:36:56.620
like it's going to take me
a while to get anywhere.

00:36:56.620 --> 00:37:00.600
And I wonder if there's
something, a few techniques

00:37:00.600 --> 00:37:03.680
that you could use to, for
instance, compress some of the

00:37:03.680 --> 00:37:04.180
information.

00:37:04.180 --> 00:37:07.850
You know, once I've seen the
photos, I may-- and this is

00:37:07.850 --> 00:37:09.560
why I asked about
the headers--

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:12.270
I may be able to locate the
card that I'm looking for

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:14.040
afterwards just by looking
at the headers.

00:37:14.040 --> 00:37:17.715
So you could do something like
slide cards over the top of

00:37:17.715 --> 00:37:23.755
one another or shrink them down
or something once the

00:37:23.755 --> 00:37:27.860
user has seen them so that
getting to the bottom or

00:37:27.860 --> 00:37:31.400
navigating around doesn't
take as many swipes.

00:37:31.400 --> 00:37:32.920
RETO MEIER: Yeah, you could use
a similar approach to what

00:37:32.920 --> 00:37:36.120
we have in Google now, where
some of the cards sort of

00:37:36.120 --> 00:37:38.620
consist of other cards layered
on top of each other that you

00:37:38.620 --> 00:37:40.990
press to expand or move
around that way.

00:37:40.990 --> 00:37:44.410
It could be quite interesting.

00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:46.400
Yeah, it's a very
attractive-looking app.

00:37:46.400 --> 00:37:49.820
It's interesting the way you've
implemented a sliding

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:52.950
drawer for search.

00:37:52.950 --> 00:37:55.150
So this is basically where you
have your categories, as well

00:37:55.150 --> 00:37:57.233
as the actual searching,
is that right?

00:37:57.233 --> 00:37:58.670
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
that's right.

00:37:58.670 --> 00:38:00.020
So that's all the
main markets.

00:38:00.020 --> 00:38:02.800
And there are more markets
to be added onto that.

00:38:02.800 --> 00:38:03.510
RETO MEIER: OK.

00:38:03.510 --> 00:38:06.870
And I assume that what I'm
reading on screen here means

00:38:06.870 --> 00:38:08.430
search Finn.

00:38:08.430 --> 00:38:09.500
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
so that's a global

00:38:09.500 --> 00:38:11.960
search for all the markets.

00:38:11.960 --> 00:38:12.870
RETO MEIER: Cool.

00:38:12.870 --> 00:38:15.630
What do you think about the idea
of using a drawer pattern

00:38:15.630 --> 00:38:19.730
for search categories, Roman?

00:38:19.730 --> 00:38:22.060
ROMAN NURIK: Overall, my
feedback here is that the

00:38:22.060 --> 00:38:24.890
drawer, like you mentioned in
the beginning, the drawer

00:38:24.890 --> 00:38:27.370
being used in different ways
as well as hierarchy within

00:38:27.370 --> 00:38:31.000
the drawer, actually having a
back button or I guess up

00:38:31.000 --> 00:38:34.570
within the drawer is going to
lead folks to be somewhat

00:38:34.570 --> 00:38:37.760
confused because you end up
creating lots of modes and

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:40.726
states where I could
actually see the--

00:38:40.726 --> 00:38:44.960
I could get the drawer to its
child screen, like what you

00:38:44.960 --> 00:38:47.660
have now, slide over
the content.

00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:51.360
And then maybe a few minutes
later, I slide over to expand,

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:57.350
and I completely forgot the
drawer was in the mode of a

00:38:57.350 --> 00:38:58.350
child view.

00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:01.900
So there's a lot of hierarchy
in the drawer.

00:39:01.900 --> 00:39:04.910
There's a lot of different
states for the drawer.

00:39:04.910 --> 00:39:06.930
I'd really try to
simplify that.

00:39:06.930 --> 00:39:09.280
The other thing is that we
obviously do have guidelines.

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:11.090
I don't want to talk too much
about guidelines here.

00:39:11.090 --> 00:39:13.860
But we do have navigation
drawer guidelines.

00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:15.910
These do depart quite
a bit from there.

00:39:15.910 --> 00:39:19.340
So if possible, I would
try to follow those.

00:39:19.340 --> 00:39:21.990
And really, once you start
searching, once you start

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:25.090
going into the flow of doing a
search, you may want to just

00:39:25.090 --> 00:39:29.240
replace the main content
with the search filter.

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:31.984
That might simplify things.

00:39:31.984 --> 00:39:34.950
RETO MEIER: Yeah, I think
you're absolutely right.

00:39:34.950 --> 00:39:37.230
I think that's where it gets
confusing is that once you're

00:39:37.230 --> 00:39:40.840
on this screen here, then
search actually

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.710
means refine search.

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:46.510
Which is fine, except that it's
different from what you

00:39:46.510 --> 00:39:49.540
have in the home screen, where
search means allow me to

00:39:49.540 --> 00:39:51.430
search or let me sort
by category.

00:39:51.430 --> 00:39:54.660
So it's kind of different
content, even if it's related.

00:39:54.660 --> 00:39:58.230
I also always find it a little
bit disconcerting when you

00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:00.390
have two sliding panels.

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:03.620
So we have the sliding drawer
on the left search, and we

00:40:03.620 --> 00:40:07.850
have the sliding drawer on
the right for logging in.

00:40:07.850 --> 00:40:10.630
That, particularly this login
piece, feels like it should be

00:40:10.630 --> 00:40:13.290
part of an action bar or
something like that.

00:40:13.290 --> 00:40:16.855
I think this is very
non-discoverable.

00:40:16.855 --> 00:40:19.310
And I assume that pressing
that is the same thing.

00:40:19.310 --> 00:40:21.210
So you press the profile
button, and

00:40:21.210 --> 00:40:23.622
that drags it across.

00:40:23.622 --> 00:40:28.370
But I think the idea of the way
that we use the sliding

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:31.210
panels and the drawers, as
Roman says, this is very

00:40:31.210 --> 00:40:33.025
different from the way we have
them in the design guidelines.

00:40:33.025 --> 00:40:35.400
And so it can be a little
bit disconcerting or

00:40:35.400 --> 00:40:38.050
counter-intuitive to users who
are expecting it to in a

00:40:38.050 --> 00:40:38.710
certain way.

00:40:38.710 --> 00:40:39.680
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:40:39.680 --> 00:40:43.920
It's sad, though, because it's
absolutely beautiful.

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:48.950
The action here and the
animation, the colors, it's

00:40:48.950 --> 00:40:52.952
just really, really nice.

00:40:52.952 --> 00:40:58.920
And I'd love to see some of
those elements kept, but you

00:40:58.920 --> 00:41:01.970
have to think about what
are your users going be

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:03.470
experienced with.

00:41:03.470 --> 00:41:05.935
It's always tempting to go with
an entirely new design.

00:41:09.210 --> 00:41:12.240
It's also very tempting
sometimes to import a design

00:41:12.240 --> 00:41:14.860
from another mobile
device family.

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:17.370
But you have to remember,
someone who's had their

00:41:17.370 --> 00:41:21.560
Android phone for a while, who
loves it, will have interacted

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:26.320
with a lot of apps that offer
similar navigation and

00:41:26.320 --> 00:41:28.290
functionality to yours, perhaps

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:29.890
in a different vertical.

00:41:29.890 --> 00:41:33.490
And this will be a learning
experience, and learning

00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:36.250
experiences are sometimes fun,
but they're often frustrating

00:41:36.250 --> 00:41:40.102
when you have a task in mind
that you want to get done.

00:41:40.102 --> 00:41:41.000
MALE SPEAKER: All right.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:43.850
I just wanted to mention that
we're actually struggling a

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:47.010
little bit to find a
suitable pattern.

00:41:47.010 --> 00:41:51.810
So we did look through quite a
few Android apps and Android

00:41:51.810 --> 00:41:54.390
guidelines looking for something
that sort of

00:41:54.390 --> 00:41:58.760
combined drilling into your
markets and also having the

00:41:58.760 --> 00:42:00.100
filters there.

00:42:00.100 --> 00:42:03.860
Another reason we did it like
this was because it scaled up

00:42:03.860 --> 00:42:05.910
quite nicely when you're
on a tablet.

00:42:05.910 --> 00:42:10.720
So you can have the filter
constantly available on the

00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:13.740
left hand side, so you can tweak
the filters while seeing

00:42:13.740 --> 00:42:16.600
real-time updates of
the results on

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:18.850
the right hand side.

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:19.550
So it works.

00:42:19.550 --> 00:42:23.290
We thought this was something
that kind of-- we know that

00:42:23.290 --> 00:42:24.300
it's not optimal.

00:42:24.300 --> 00:42:28.225
But we didn't find a better
solution, to be honest.

00:42:28.225 --> 00:42:29.370
RETO MEIER: Yeah, I hear
what you're saying.

00:42:29.370 --> 00:42:32.650
I think for the tablet layout,
it would look great.

00:42:32.650 --> 00:42:34.815
I think it's exactly the sort of
layout that you want to use

00:42:34.815 --> 00:42:37.570
where you have everything
on screen.

00:42:37.570 --> 00:42:39.835
Here, it almost feels
as though--

00:42:39.835 --> 00:42:46.100
I think it's, as well, rather
than any individual problem,

00:42:46.100 --> 00:42:48.760
it's more of a combination of
a lot of paradigms that are

00:42:48.760 --> 00:42:50.705
being used slightly differently
from how you

00:42:50.705 --> 00:42:51.730
would expect it.

00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:56.070
And so then as an experienced
Android user, you start to get

00:42:56.070 --> 00:42:59.670
confused as to what you need
to do to navigate around.

00:42:59.670 --> 00:43:01.090
It's primarily around
navigation.

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:06.100
So here, for example, I'm
expecting to be able to swat

00:43:06.100 --> 00:43:08.090
to bring something back,
but I can't.

00:43:08.090 --> 00:43:12.420
Here, it's back, which is an up
button which looks similar

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:14.370
to what I would expect
an up button to be,

00:43:14.370 --> 00:43:15.640
but it looks different.

00:43:15.640 --> 00:43:18.950
So it, again, gives me that
pause for thought, like, what

00:43:18.950 --> 00:43:20.780
is this going to do?

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:23.605
So you're never quite sure how
to navigate back to where

00:43:23.605 --> 00:43:24.000
you're from.

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:27.710
Because here I need to either
hit back, or I need to bring

00:43:27.710 --> 00:43:30.360
my navigation drawer back and
then hit back in order to

00:43:30.360 --> 00:43:31.630
return to the previous menu.

00:43:31.630 --> 00:43:33.305
That's kind of unexpected.

00:43:33.305 --> 00:43:36.320
I never expect to have to slide
out a drawer before I'm

00:43:36.320 --> 00:43:39.826
able to navigate back
up in the hierarchy.

00:43:39.826 --> 00:43:43.610
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now I'm going to
take a slightly contradictory

00:43:43.610 --> 00:43:49.540
position to Reto and say, this
app feels very designed.

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:53.740
And it feels like every
interview, that I have, every

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:57.670
question I have about
navigation, is solved in an

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:00.540
elegant matter.

00:44:00.540 --> 00:44:04.042
I do agree that it's completely
non-standard, but I

00:44:04.042 --> 00:44:05.580
think we should recognize
that a lot of thought

00:44:05.580 --> 00:44:06.990
has gone into this.

00:44:06.990 --> 00:44:08.530
And there's some interesting
problems.

00:44:08.530 --> 00:44:11.763
What I would really love to see,
if Roman's up for it, is

00:44:11.763 --> 00:44:14.580
to have this be an "Android
Design in Action" candidate

00:44:14.580 --> 00:44:17.920
and talk a little bit about the
challenges that you faced,

00:44:17.920 --> 00:44:22.140
how you solved them, and see if
we can find something that

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:24.240
fits into the Android
standard that

00:44:24.240 --> 00:44:25.687
solves the mess elegantly.

00:44:25.687 --> 00:44:26.940
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:44:26.940 --> 00:44:30.440
ROMAN NURIK: There's a lot
of hierarchy here.

00:44:30.440 --> 00:44:32.700
That's one of the hardest things
you can deal with as a

00:44:32.700 --> 00:44:34.610
designer is dealing with
different hierarchies and

00:44:34.610 --> 00:44:37.850
different flows as well as,
obviously, what you mentioned

00:44:37.850 --> 00:44:40.950
before, the tablet versus
[INAUDIBLE].

00:44:40.950 --> 00:44:43.140
How do things work, how
do things respond

00:44:43.140 --> 00:44:44.330
to different sizes?

00:44:44.330 --> 00:44:46.410
Definitely, in the next few
episodes of "Android Design in

00:44:46.410 --> 00:44:51.265
Action," we were looking to get
back into the redesign or

00:44:51.265 --> 00:44:52.910
the re-imagining world.

00:44:52.910 --> 00:44:55.980
So definitely, this is one of
the apps I would consider.

00:44:55.980 --> 00:44:57.720
RETO MEIER: I think it's
one of the challenges.

00:44:57.720 --> 00:45:01.000
I've seen this a lot from apps
which are trying to do some

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:03.510
sort of shopping, or anything
where you have to navigate

00:45:03.510 --> 00:45:07.240
through multiple categories
and do multiple sort of

00:45:07.240 --> 00:45:09.820
filtering on each of
those categories

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:10.920
becomes a real challenge.

00:45:10.920 --> 00:45:14.250
I've seen people try and do it
using drop-downs in the action

00:45:14.250 --> 00:45:18.930
bar or having the filter
controls here on the top of

00:45:18.930 --> 00:45:19.315
the screen.

00:45:19.315 --> 00:45:21.070
But then that obscures
all of the content.

00:45:21.070 --> 00:45:24.130
So yeah, I've seen a
lot of apps try.

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:27.310
And having that sort of
multi-level hierarchy is

00:45:27.310 --> 00:45:28.140
definitely a challenge.

00:45:28.140 --> 00:45:32.330
So I would be very interested to
see what Rowan and his team

00:45:32.330 --> 00:45:35.400
can come up with as possible
alternatives.

00:45:35.400 --> 00:45:37.020
ROMAN NURIK: One minor t I
wanted to call out here.

00:45:37.020 --> 00:45:40.370
So this kind of starts feeling
a little bit like this is

00:45:40.370 --> 00:45:44.530
solving the problem of
master/detail, you have master

00:45:44.530 --> 00:45:47.910
gets-- when you actually go
into search, you have the

00:45:47.910 --> 00:45:50.460
search filter.

00:45:50.460 --> 00:45:53.675
It takes a little bit of mental
gymnastics to see it,

00:45:53.675 --> 00:45:57.250
but maybe it's like a master
on the left and

00:45:57.250 --> 00:45:58.490
detail on the right.

00:45:58.490 --> 00:46:03.290
And what you end up having is
basically you're now in the

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:06.920
cars or the guitars or things.

00:46:06.920 --> 00:46:07.070
RETO MEIER: Motorcycles, baby.

00:46:07.070 --> 00:46:08.530
ROMAN NURIK: Yeah.

00:46:08.530 --> 00:46:11.060
And pressing up should actually
take you back to the

00:46:11.060 --> 00:46:13.600
top with the stream and the
navigation on the left.

00:46:13.600 --> 00:46:16.200
So basically, you have
two activities.

00:46:16.200 --> 00:46:18.250
At the top, you have the
screen as well as the

00:46:18.250 --> 00:46:19.330
navigation drawer.

00:46:19.330 --> 00:46:23.310
But as soon as you jump into
cars or something else, you

00:46:23.310 --> 00:46:26.460
get taken to a new activity with
a sliding pane layout,

00:46:26.460 --> 00:46:32.020
which works on tablet as well as
phone, where the left side

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:36.370
